<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Density Range" class="currentChild" href="Density_Range">Density Range</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In printing, any non-uniformity in the density of a printed image, resulting from fading, discoloration, incomplete ink coverage, or other causes. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In imaging, <em>density range</em> refers to the <a title="Gamut" href="Gamut">gamut</a> of tones in an original (or reproduction), expressed as the difference between the area of maximum density (the darkest portions of an image) and the minimum density (the lightest tones). Also known as <a title="Tonal Range" href="Tonal_Range">tonal range</a>. For example, the density of a <a title="Shadow" href="Shadow">shadow</a> area can be calculated as, say, 2.5. The density of a <a title="Highlight" href="Highlight">highlight</a> area can be calculated as 0.10. Thus, the density range for the image as a whole would be 2.4. (For the formula regarding the calculation of density, see <a title="Density" href="Density">Density</a>.) Also known as <a title="Tonal Range" href="Tonal_Range">tonal range</a> and <a title="Dynamic Range" href="Dynamic_Range">dynamic range</a>. 
</p>
